1
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:46,467
<i>NIXON ON TAPE:
They'd better not
push me on him,</i>

2
00:00:46,535 --> 00:00:47,968
<i>or I'll just kick
them in the teeth on it.</i>

3
00:00:48,036 --> 00:00:50,334
<i>NIXON AIDE:
Well, I think, if they...</i>

4
00:00:53,608 --> 00:00:55,542
<i>NIXON: ...Internal Revenue
people that are kicking</i>

5
00:00:55,610 --> 00:00:58,204
<i>Billy Graham around
is Rosenberg.</i>

6
00:00:58,280 --> 00:01:00,077
<i>He is to be out.</i>

7
00:01:00,148 --> 00:01:02,241
<i>I don't give a goddamn
what the story is.</i>

8
00:01:02,317 --> 00:01:03,875
<i>He went on television.</i>

9
00:01:05,921 --> 00:01:07,684
<i>I have not.
I've already
ordered Connally,</i>

10
00:01:07,756 --> 00:01:09,451
<i>we're going
after the Chandlers,</i>

11
00:01:09,524 --> 00:01:11,583
<i>every one individually,
collectively,</i>

12
00:01:11,660 --> 00:01:13,651
<i>their income taxes
are starting this week.</i>

13
00:01:13,729 --> 00:01:16,425
<i>Every one of those
sons of bitches.</i>

14
00:01:18,800 --> 00:01:21,599
<i>NIXON: Well, this is
something that we can
really hang Teddy or...</i>

15
00:01:21,671 --> 00:01:22,660
<i>MAN: Yeah.</i>

16
00:01:22,739 --> 00:01:24,036
<i>NIXON: ...or the
Kennedy clan with.</i>

17
00:01:24,107 --> 00:01:26,371
<i>I'm gonna want to put that
in Colson's hands.</i>

18
00:01:26,442 --> 00:01:28,603
<i>And we're gonna
want to run with it.</i>

19
00:01:30,947 --> 00:01:32,812
<i>NEWS REPORTER 1:
A controversial
day in politics.</i>

20
00:01:32,882 --> 00:01:35,248
<i>A man arrested trying
to bug the offices</i>

21
00:01:35,318 --> 00:01:37,980
<i>of the Democratic
National Committee
in Washington</i>

22
00:01:38,054 --> 00:01:39,351
<i>turns out to be an employee</i>

23
00:01:39,422 --> 00:01:42,515
<i>of President Richard Nixon's
re-election
campaign committee.</i>

24
00:01:42,591 --> 00:01:45,993
<i>He is one of five
persons surprised
and arrested yesterday</i>

25
00:01:46,062 --> 00:01:48,496
<i>inside the headquarters
of the Democratic
National Committee</i>

26
00:01:48,564 --> 00:01:49,758
<i>in Washington.</i>

27
00:01:49,832 --> 00:01:51,322
<i>And guess what else he is.</i>

28
00:01:51,401 --> 00:01:53,369
<i>A consultant of
President Richard Nixon's</i>

29
00:01:53,436 --> 00:01:55,370
<i>re-election
campaign committee.</i>

30
00:01:55,438 --> 00:01:57,429
<i>NEWS REPORTER 2:
The trial started today
at the federal courthouse</i>

31
00:01:57,507 --> 00:01:59,134
<i>for the five burglars
caught breaking into</i>

32
00:01:59,208 --> 00:02:02,006
<i>the Democratic National
Party headquarters.</i>

33
00:02:02,078 --> 00:02:03,170
<i>CAMERAMAN: Stand by
for camera.</i>

34
00:02:03,246 --> 00:02:05,770
<i>MUDD: John Dean,
the ex-White House Counsel,
testified today</i>

35
00:02:05,847 --> 00:02:08,874
<i>that President Nixon
knew about
the Watergate cover-up.</i>

36
00:02:09,719 --> 00:02:11,209
<i>DEAN: At one point in
the conversation,</i>

37
00:02:11,287 --> 00:02:12,720
<i>I recall the President
telling me</i>

38
00:02:12,789 --> 00:02:16,225
<i>to keep a good list
of the press people
giving us trouble</i>

39
00:02:16,292 --> 00:02:19,591
<i>because we will make
life difficult for them
after the election.</i>

40
00:02:19,662 --> 00:02:22,426
<i>NEWS REPORTER 3:
Dean read through
a 245-page statement</i>

41
00:02:22,498 --> 00:02:25,058
<i>characterizing a president
who was easily outraged</i>

42
00:02:25,134 --> 00:02:27,897
<i>over war protesters
and political adversaries,</i>

43
00:02:27,969 --> 00:02:29,801
<i>and outlining
a range of offenses,</i>

44
00:02:29,872 --> 00:02:31,636
<i>including wiretapping
of newsmen,</i>

45
00:02:31,708 --> 00:02:33,835
<i>a Charles Colson
plan to firebomb</i>

46
00:02:33,911 --> 00:02:35,970
<i>and burglarize
the Brookings Institution,</i>

47
00:02:36,046 --> 00:02:39,015
<i>and spying on
Senator Kennedy
and other Democrats.</i>

48
00:02:39,083 --> 00:02:42,519
<i>LAWYER: The misuse
of power is the very
essence of tyranny.</i>

49
00:02:42,586 --> 00:02:44,645
<i>And consider, if you will,</i>

50
00:02:44,721 --> 00:02:48,680
<i>the frightening
implications of that
for a free society.</i>

51
00:02:49,026 --> 00:02:52,893
<i>NEWS REPORTER 4: The President
today accepted the resignation
of three of his closest aides.</i>

52
00:02:52,962 --> 00:02:55,557
<i>Out is H.R. Haldeman,
Chief of Staff.</i>

53
00:02:55,632 --> 00:02:58,123
<i>Also quitting under fire
is John Ehrlichman.</i>

54
00:02:58,202 --> 00:03:00,466
<i>Ehrlichman was
a key political advisor.</i>

55
00:03:00,537 --> 00:03:01,765
<i>NEWS REPORTER 5: Good morning.
The Supreme Court</i>

56
00:03:01,839 --> 00:03:03,466
<i>has just ruled on
the tapes controversy,</i>

57
00:03:03,540 --> 00:03:05,872
<i>and here is Carl Stern,
who has that ruling.</i>

58
00:03:05,943 --> 00:03:08,275
<i>It is a unanimous
decision, Doug, eight to zero.</i>

59
00:03:08,345 --> 00:03:10,643
<i>Justice Rehnquist
took no part in the decision</i>

60
00:03:10,714 --> 00:03:14,581
<i>ordering the President
of the United States
to turn over the tapes.</i>

61
00:03:14,650 --> 00:03:16,777
<i>(CROWD CHEERING)</i>

62
00:03:16,853 --> 00:03:19,015
<i>It's an eight-to-zero
unanimous opinion.</i>

63
00:03:19,089 --> 00:03:20,818
<i>A White House aide
told NBC News today</i>

64
00:03:20,891 --> 00:03:22,586
<i>that impeachment
of the President</i>

65
00:03:22,659 --> 00:03:26,459
<i>by the full
House of Representatives
now is a virtual certainty.</i>

66
00:03:28,332 --> 00:03:30,266
<i>These are,
with no serious doubt,</i>

67
00:03:30,334 --> 00:03:33,770
<i>the last hours
of the 37th presidency
of the United States.</i>

68
00:03:38,041 --> 00:03:40,236
<i>This is indeed
an historic day,</i>

69
00:03:40,310 --> 00:03:43,940
<i>the only time
a president has ever
resigned from office</i>

70
00:03:44,015 --> 00:03:46,677
<i>in our nearly 200
years of history.</i>

71
00:03:46,751 --> 00:03:49,652
<i>You see the White House
there, and in the White House,</i>

72
00:03:49,721 --> 00:03:51,052
<i>in just a few moments now,</i>

73
00:03:51,122 --> 00:03:54,216
<i>President Nixon
will be appearing
before the people,</i>

74
00:03:54,292 --> 00:03:58,193
<i>perhaps for the last
time as President
of the United States.</i>

75
00:03:59,563 --> 00:04:01,758
<i>WHITE HOUSE DIRECTOR:
15 seconds, Mr. President.</i>

76
00:04:07,639 --> 00:04:11,336
<i>Okay, that's five,
four, three...</i>

77
00:04:15,180 --> 00:04:18,308
<i>Good evening.
This is the 37th time</i>

78
00:04:18,383 --> 00:04:21,112
I have spoken to you
from this office

79
00:04:21,185 --> 00:04:23,745
where so many decisions
have been made

80
00:04:23,820 --> 00:04:26,345
<i>that have shaped
the history of our nation.</i>

81
00:04:26,423 --> 00:04:28,414
<i>I remember exactly
where I was.</i>

82
00:04:29,827 --> 00:04:33,194
<i>My father called.
The phone rang, my father
called and he said,</i>

83
00:04:33,264 --> 00:04:36,529
<i>"Turn on the TV right now.
Richard Nixon's going down."</i>

84
00:04:36,601 --> 00:04:40,332
<i>I was at home with friends,
and we were watching
television at home.</i>

85
00:04:40,405 --> 00:04:43,202
<i>We stayed up and,
like everyone else,
I'd been glued to</i>

86
00:04:43,273 --> 00:04:45,764
<i>the Select and Judiciary
Committee hearings
night after night.</i>

87
00:04:45,842 --> 00:04:47,970
<i>And then finally,
it had come to this.</i>

88
00:04:48,046 --> 00:04:53,849
<i>Therefore, I shall resign
the presidency effective
at noon tomorrow.</i>

89
00:04:53,919 --> 00:04:56,911
<i>But instead of
the satisfaction
I imagined I'd feel,</i>

90
00:04:56,989 --> 00:04:59,253
I just got angrier
and angrier,

91
00:04:59,325 --> 00:05:02,089
<i>because there was
no admission of guilt.</i>

92
00:05:02,161 --> 00:05:03,594
<i>There was no apology.</i>

93
00:05:03,662 --> 00:05:05,061
Little did I know

94
00:05:05,130 --> 00:05:07,256
that I would one day
be part of the team

95
00:05:07,332 --> 00:05:09,732
<i>that would try and
elicit that apology.</i>

96
00:05:09,801 --> 00:05:12,827
NIXON: To leave office
before my term is completed

97
00:05:12,904 --> 00:05:15,896
<i>is abhorrent to every
instinct in my body.</i>

98
00:05:15,974 --> 00:05:18,466
<i>I have never been a quitter.</i>

99
00:05:18,544 --> 00:05:20,205
And that that team
would be led

100
00:05:20,279 --> 00:05:23,976
by the most unlikely
of white knights,

101
00:05:24,049 --> 00:05:25,983
a man with no
political convictions
whatsoever,

102
00:05:26,051 --> 00:05:30,282
<i>a man who, as far as I know,
had never even voted
once in his life.</i>

103
00:05:31,089 --> 00:05:35,219
<i>But he was a man who had
one big advantage
over the rest of us.</i>

104
00:05:36,494 --> 00:05:38,792
<i>He understood television.</i>

105
00:05:39,330 --> 00:05:41,492
<i>(FROST OVER AUSTRALIA
THEME MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

106
00:05:45,337 --> 00:05:50,400
<i>ANNOUNCER: And now,
the host of
Frost Over Australia,</i>

107
00:05:50,476 --> 00:05:53,103
<i>Mr. David Frost!</i>

108
00:05:53,278 --> 00:05:54,302
(CHUCKLES)

109
00:05:54,379 --> 00:05:56,974
<i>Thank you, thank you.</i>

110
00:05:58,784 --> 00:06:00,376
<i>Hello. Good evening.</i>

111
00:06:00,452 --> 00:06:03,581
And with the eyes of the world
focused on the White House,

112
00:06:03,657 --> 00:06:06,285
here in Australia,
burglars have broken into

113
00:06:06,359 --> 00:06:08,691
a meat factory in Brisbane

114
00:06:08,762 --> 00:06:11,595
<i>and stolen a ton
of pork sausages.</i>

115
00:06:11,665 --> 00:06:12,757
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

116
00:06:12,832 --> 00:06:17,495
<i>The Queensland police are
looking for men
in a long, thin getaway car.</i>

117
00:06:20,539 --> 00:06:22,234
<i>Now, my first guest tonight...</i>

118
00:06:22,308 --> 00:06:23,468
Well, we in the Nixon camp

119
00:06:23,542 --> 00:06:25,009
<i>really didn't know that much
about David Frost,</i>

120
00:06:25,077 --> 00:06:28,070
other than he was
a British talk show host

121
00:06:28,148 --> 00:06:29,911
<i>with something of
a playboy reputation.</i>

122
00:06:29,983 --> 00:06:33,714
<i>He'd had a talk show
here in the US that
had won some awards</i>

123
00:06:33,787 --> 00:06:38,883
<i>but hadn't syndicated well
and had been dropped
by the network.</i>

124
00:06:38,957 --> 00:06:40,447
He ended up taking
it down to Australia,

125
00:06:40,526 --> 00:06:44,257
<i>which is, I believe,
where he was when
the President resigned.</i>

126
00:06:44,530 --> 00:06:47,021
<i>FROST: Next week's guest
will be Evonne Goolagong.</i>

127
00:06:47,099 --> 00:06:48,999
<i>We'll see you then.
God bless.</i>

128
00:06:51,805 --> 00:06:53,500
<i>Great show, David.
Thanks, Noah.</i>

129
00:06:53,573 --> 00:06:54,767
<i>NOAH: Come and look at this.</i>

130
00:06:54,841 --> 00:06:55,967
<i>Nixon leaving
the White House.</i>

131
00:06:56,042 --> 00:06:58,771
<i>NEWS REPORTER: A dark day
for Richard Nixon,
who has drawn crowds</i>

132
00:06:58,844 --> 00:07:00,209
<i>to the vast Ellipse south
of the White House before.</i>

133
00:07:00,279 --> 00:07:01,803
<i>What, this is live?
Yeah.</i>

134
00:07:01,880 --> 00:07:04,543
<i>NEWS REPORTER:
But those were triumphs.
This is not.</i>

135
00:07:04,617 --> 00:07:07,108
What time is it
in Washington?

136
00:07:07,187 --> 00:07:08,620
<i>9:00 a.m.</i>

137
00:07:08,688 --> 00:07:09,814
<i>Why didn't he wait?</i>

138
00:07:09,889 --> 00:07:11,356
<i>It's 6:00 in the morning
on the West Coast.</i>

139
00:07:11,424 --> 00:07:13,517
<i>Half his audience
is still asleep.</i>

140
00:07:15,062 --> 00:07:17,895
<i>All right,
you blokes, let's get
the set broken down.</i>

141
00:07:17,965 --> 00:07:22,025
<i>NEWS REPORTER: ...are
witnesses to the saddest day
in the life of Richard Nixon,</i>

142
00:07:22,102 --> 00:07:26,038
<i>his last moments
as President
of the United States,</i>

143
00:07:26,106 --> 00:07:29,735
<i>a moment unlike
any other in the history
of this country.</i>

144
00:07:46,726 --> 00:07:48,591
<i>Richard Nixon, who goes now</i>

145
00:07:48,661 --> 00:07:50,925
<i>from the power
of the presidency</i>

146
00:07:50,997 --> 00:07:53,227
<i>to a form of exile
in California.</i>

147
00:07:53,299 --> 00:07:56,097
<i>Find out the numbers
for this, will you?
Worldwide.</i>

148
00:08:09,582 --> 00:08:11,482
<i>BRENNAN: I remember his face.</i>

149
00:08:12,987 --> 00:08:15,319
<i>Staring out the window.</i>

150
00:08:15,389 --> 00:08:20,053
<i>Down below him,
a liberal America
cheered, gloated.</i>

151
00:08:21,762 --> 00:08:24,287
Hippies, draft dodgers,
dilettantes,

152
00:08:24,365 --> 00:08:27,733
<i>the same people
who'd spit on me when
I got back from Vietnam.</i>

153
00:08:28,904 --> 00:08:32,930
<i>They'd gotten rid
of Richard Nixon,
their bogeyman.</i>

154
00:08:45,619 --> 00:08:48,646
<i>So what's so important
that it couldn't wait,
that it had to be today?</i>

155
00:08:48,723 --> 00:08:53,159
<i>I've had an idea, John,
rather a bold idea
for an interview.</i>

156
00:08:53,227 --> 00:08:54,694
<i>Fish and chips, please.</i>

157
00:08:54,762 --> 00:08:56,161
<i>And in a moment...</i>

158
00:08:56,230 --> 00:08:57,595
<i>Well, it's too late now.
It's done.</i>

159
00:08:57,665 --> 00:08:58,996
<i>I've called his people...</i>

160
00:08:59,066 --> 00:09:00,226
You?

161
00:09:00,301 --> 00:09:02,667
<i>Beans, peas and lamb, please.</i>

162
00:09:02,736 --> 00:09:04,203
<i>And made an offer.</i>

163
00:09:04,271 --> 00:09:08,731
Now, if the subject
were to say yes,

164
00:09:10,644 --> 00:09:16,139
<i>well, he's rather
a big fish that swims
in not-untricky waters.</i>

165
00:09:16,650 --> 00:09:20,416
<i>So it goes without saying
that I'd want a dear friend</i>

166
00:09:20,488 --> 00:09:23,322
<i>and the finest producer
I know by my side.</i>

167
00:09:28,463 --> 00:09:29,657
So who is it?

168
00:09:31,066 --> 00:09:32,863
<i>Richard Nixon.</i>

169
00:09:32,968 --> 00:09:35,597
(LAUGHS) Richard Nixon?

170
00:09:35,671 --> 00:09:38,070
<i>Well, come on,
don't look like that.</i>

171
00:09:38,139 --> 00:09:39,800
Well, how would you
expect me to look?

172
00:09:39,875 --> 00:09:43,140
<i>I spent yesterday
evening watching you
interview the Bee Gees.</i>

173
00:09:43,211 --> 00:09:45,076
<i>Weren't they terrific?</i>

174
00:09:45,146 --> 00:09:49,139
<i>Come on, John,
we've done political
interviews before.</i>

175
00:09:50,418 --> 00:09:52,909
So, okay, so what
kind of interview?

176
00:09:52,988 --> 00:09:58,221
<i>A full, extensive
look-back over his life,
his presidency.</i>

177
00:09:58,293 --> 00:09:59,852
And?

178
00:09:59,928 --> 00:10:01,361
<i>And what?
Come on, David.</i>

179
00:10:01,429 --> 00:10:02,896
Surely the only thing
that would interest anyone

180
00:10:02,964 --> 00:10:05,296
<i>about Richard Nixon
would be a confession.</i>

181
00:10:05,367 --> 00:10:07,130
<i>A full,
no-holds-barred
confession.</i>

182
00:10:07,202 --> 00:10:09,432
<i>Well, we'll get that, too.</i>

183
00:10:09,504 --> 00:10:10,493
From Richard Nixon?

184
00:10:10,572 --> 00:10:11,903
<i>Come on, John.</i>

185
00:10:11,973 --> 00:10:14,271
<i>Just think of the
numbers it would get.</i>

186
00:10:15,010 --> 00:10:16,671
Do you know how
many people watched

187
00:10:16,745 --> 00:10:18,372
his farewell speech
in the White House?

188
00:10:18,446 --> 00:10:20,471
<i>Four hundred million.</i>

189
00:10:21,850 --> 00:10:23,841
<i>But in the end,
David heard nothing.</i>

190
00:10:23,919 --> 00:10:25,580
And soon after
arriving in California,

191
00:10:25,654 --> 00:10:29,249
<i>Nixon was rushed
to hospital with an acute
attack of phlebitis.</i>

192
00:10:42,705 --> 00:10:45,139
<i>I think it was
around this time
that Gerald Ford,</i>

193
00:10:45,207 --> 00:10:46,230
who was the new President,

194
00:10:46,309 --> 00:10:48,368
and who was desperate
to move the agenda
on from Watergate,

195
00:10:48,444 --> 00:10:51,538
<i>gave Nixon a full,
free and absolute pardon.</i>

196
00:10:51,614 --> 00:10:54,344
<i>Now therefore, I,
Gerald R. Ford,</i>

197
00:10:54,417 --> 00:10:57,079
<i>President of
the United States,</i>

198
00:10:57,153 --> 00:11:01,089
<i>have granted,
and by these presents
do grant,</i>

199
00:11:01,157 --> 00:11:03,682
<i>a full,
free and absolute pardon</i>

200
00:11:03,759 --> 00:11:08,957
<i>unto Richard Nixon
for all offenses
against the United States.</i>

201
00:11:09,030 --> 00:11:11,431
It meant that the man
who had committed
the greatest felony

202
00:11:11,500 --> 00:11:14,162
<i>in American political history
would never stand trial.</i>

203
00:11:14,236 --> 00:11:16,636
<i>It was like he slipped
out the back door.</i>

204
00:11:17,873 --> 00:11:19,636
<i>A public opinion
poll indicates</i>

205
00:11:19,709 --> 00:11:23,076
<i>a two-to-one disapproval
of the pardoning
of Richard Nixon.</i>

206
00:11:23,145 --> 00:11:26,342
<i>CHANCELLOR: One telegram
from Virginia said,
"Roosevelt had his New Deal,</i>

207
00:11:26,415 --> 00:11:30,010
<i>"Truman had his Fair Deal,
now Ford has
his crooked deal."</i>

208
00:11:30,086 --> 00:11:32,076
<i>There was no deal, period.</i>

209
00:11:32,153 --> 00:11:34,520
<i>I don't think the truth
will ever come out.</i>

210
00:11:34,590 --> 00:11:36,251
<i>The American people
need to know the truth,</i>

211
00:11:36,325 --> 00:11:39,557
<i>and I don't think
it will ever now
be fully known.</i>

212
00:12:02,686 --> 00:12:05,519
GANNON: So how do we
want to address
the college protests?

213
00:12:05,589 --> 00:12:06,783
Well, do we want
to lift some quotes

214
00:12:06,857 --> 00:12:09,985
<i>from the "stand up
and be counted" speech
in 1970?</i>

215
00:12:10,060 --> 00:12:11,687
<i>Sir?
GANNON: You know, maybe
we're just better off</i>

216
00:12:11,762 --> 00:12:13,286
<i>using the whole
Lincoln Memorial memo.</i>

217
00:12:13,363 --> 00:12:14,830
<i>SAWYER: Just include
the whole thing.</i>

218
00:12:14,898 --> 00:12:17,365
<i>Mr. President,
Swifty Lazar is here.</i>

219
00:12:17,433 --> 00:12:19,697
<i>Okay. No, no, stick around.</i>

220
00:12:19,769 --> 00:12:21,965
<i>You're gonna get
a kick out of this.</i>

221
00:12:22,039 --> 00:12:25,270
<i>This is my literary agent
from Hollywood.</i>

222
00:12:25,342 --> 00:12:27,537
<i>Hygiene obsessive.</i>

223
00:12:30,447 --> 00:12:33,007
<i>Mr. President,
good to see you.</i>

224
00:12:33,083 --> 00:12:34,710
<i>Nice to see you.</i>

225
00:12:34,785 --> 00:12:37,379
<i>These are folks
helping me with my book.</i>

226
00:12:37,454 --> 00:12:40,354
<i>Diane Sawyer,
Frank Gannon,
Irving Lazar.</i>

227
00:12:40,423 --> 00:12:41,981
<i>Nice to meet you.
Miss Sawyer.</i>

228
00:12:42,058 --> 00:12:43,787
<i>Pleasure.
Mr. Gannon.</i>

229
00:12:47,698 --> 00:12:49,724
<i>Okay, that's it.
I'll see you after lunch.</i>

230
00:12:49,801 --> 00:12:51,792
SWIFTY: So how
you feeling, sir?

231
00:12:52,203 --> 00:12:56,765
<i>I'm better, thank you.
Though not yet
well enough to golf,</i>

232
00:12:57,608 --> 00:13:00,475
<i>thank God.
I despise that game.</i>

233
00:13:01,478 --> 00:13:04,003
Imagine, six weeks
out of office

234
00:13:04,081 --> 00:13:06,606
as President
of the United States,

235
00:13:06,683 --> 00:13:09,551
<i>and they'd have me putting
in my hospital room.</i>

236
00:13:09,620 --> 00:13:11,611
<i>Never retire, Mr. Lazar.</i>

237
00:13:12,056 --> 00:13:16,993
<i>To me, the unhappiest
people of the world
are retired.</i>

238
00:13:17,061 --> 00:13:18,858
<i>No purpose.</i>

239
00:13:18,930 --> 00:13:21,694
<i>What makes life mean
something is purpose.</i>

240
00:13:21,766 --> 00:13:24,666
<i>A goal. A battle. A struggle.</i>

241
00:13:24,735 --> 00:13:26,965
<i>Well, even if
you don't win it.</i>

242
00:13:27,471 --> 00:13:29,962
When my doctor
declared me unfit

243
00:13:30,040 --> 00:13:31,872
to give testimony
in the Watergate trial,

244
00:13:31,943 --> 00:13:34,173
<i>everybody thought
I'd be relieved.</i>

245
00:13:34,245 --> 00:13:35,837
<i>Well, they were wrong.</i>

246
00:13:35,913 --> 00:13:37,437
<i>That was the lowest I got.</i>

247
00:13:37,515 --> 00:13:41,952
<i>Well, if it's a challenge
you want, here's one
you might enjoy.</i>

248
00:13:42,019 --> 00:13:45,955
<i>How to spend $2 million,
2.3 to be precise.</i>

249
00:13:46,023 --> 00:13:47,819
<i>It's what I got
for your memoirs.</i>

250
00:13:47,891 --> 00:13:49,358
<i>Well, thank you.</i>

251
00:13:49,426 --> 00:13:50,688
<i>Eh...</i>

252
00:13:50,761 --> 00:13:52,524
It might be a little short
of what I wanted,

253
00:13:52,596 --> 00:13:56,158
<i>but let me assure you,
it's a whole lot more
than they wanted.</i>

254
00:13:56,234 --> 00:13:58,260
<i>That book is important to me.</i>

255
00:13:58,337 --> 00:14:02,034
<i>It's probably the only
chance I'm gonna get
to put the record straight</i>

256
00:14:02,107 --> 00:14:05,474
<i>and remind people
the Nixon years
weren't all bad.</i>

257
00:14:06,945 --> 00:14:10,846
<i>You know, if you're trying
to put the record straight,</i>

258
00:14:10,915 --> 00:14:12,382
<i>I'd at least talk to him.</i>

259
00:14:12,450 --> 00:14:13,576
NIXON: Who?

260
00:14:14,018 --> 00:14:17,351
<i>David Frost.
English talk show guy.</i>

261
00:14:18,089 --> 00:14:20,991
Why would I want to
talk to David Frost?

262
00:14:21,059 --> 00:14:23,857
<i>Well, a while back,
he wrote asking
for an interview.</i>

263
00:14:23,929 --> 00:14:25,260
<i>No.</i>

264
00:14:25,330 --> 00:14:26,661
<i>Well, we didn't
get back to him.</i>

265
00:14:26,732 --> 00:14:29,064
<i>Frankly, we didn't
find him appropriate.</i>

266
00:14:29,134 --> 00:14:31,897
<i>Well, I thought
that we were
doing one with CBS.</i>

267
00:14:31,969 --> 00:14:33,937
<i>We are. I just figured
doing it with Frost</i>

268
00:14:34,005 --> 00:14:36,132
<i>would be a whole lot
easier than doing it
with Mike Wallace.</i>

269
00:14:36,207 --> 00:14:40,541
<i>It would, but it would
have a lot less,
you know, credibility.</i>

270
00:14:40,611 --> 00:14:44,139
<i>True, true. Could
probably get more money.</i>

271
00:14:46,952 --> 00:14:48,715
<i>Really?
Look.</i>

272
00:14:48,787 --> 00:14:52,188
<i>We'll always have
350 on the table
from CBS.</i>

273
00:14:52,257 --> 00:14:55,987
But if I could get
Frost to pay more
and secure better terms,

274
00:14:56,494 --> 00:14:58,587
<i>it might be a shame to pass.</i>

275
00:14:59,163 --> 00:15:02,360
<i>It'd be interesting to know
where he is right now.</i>

276
00:15:02,800 --> 00:15:05,394
<i>We tied him to
railway tracks,
and he escaped.</i>

277
00:15:05,939 --> 00:15:08,737
<i>We buried him alive,
and he walked free.</i>

278
00:15:08,808 --> 00:15:13,211
<i>Today we're lowering
escape artist Derek Harrison
into the water</i>

279
00:15:13,279 --> 00:15:17,612
<i>to see if he can
miraculously
cheat death once more.</i>

280
00:15:17,683 --> 00:15:20,117
<i>Good evening,
and welcome to
Great Escapes.</i>

281
00:15:20,185 --> 00:15:22,119
<i>My name is David Frost.</i>

282
00:15:24,156 --> 00:15:25,748
<i>DIRECTOR:
Okay, that is a cut.</i>

283
00:15:25,824 --> 00:15:26,916
<i>Thank you.</i>

284
00:15:26,992 --> 00:15:30,292
<i>In any deal, you need to
know your opponent's
breaking point.</i>

285
00:15:31,698 --> 00:15:33,393
To assess that,
you might call them

286
00:15:33,466 --> 00:15:35,696
<i>late at night
or at the weekend.</i>

287
00:15:36,336 --> 00:15:39,169
<i>If they take the call,
you know they're desperate.</i>

288
00:15:39,239 --> 00:15:42,674
<i>And from that moment on,
you know you have
the upper hand.</i>

289
00:15:43,208 --> 00:15:45,108
(PHONE RINGING)

290
00:15:53,753 --> 00:15:54,913
Hello?

291
00:15:54,988 --> 00:15:56,683
<i>Mr. Frost? Irving Lazar.</i>

292
00:15:58,057 --> 00:15:59,547
Who?

293
00:15:59,626 --> 00:16:02,788
<i>Swifty Lazar.
I represent
President Nixon.</i>

294
00:16:02,861 --> 00:16:04,123
What time is it?

295
00:16:04,196 --> 00:16:05,185
<i>Bad time?</i>

296
00:16:05,264 --> 00:16:08,062
<i>(STUTTERING) No! Not at all.</i>

297
00:16:11,136 --> 00:16:14,971
<i>I'm calling with regard
to your request
for an interview</i>

298
00:16:15,041 --> 00:16:18,034
and to say,
having considered it,

299
00:16:18,112 --> 00:16:22,105
<i>my client is not
necessarily opposed
to the idea.</i>

300
00:16:22,182 --> 00:16:25,912
<i>Really?
Well, that's
terrific news!</i>

301
00:16:25,985 --> 00:16:27,714
<i>For God's sake.</i>

302
00:16:27,787 --> 00:16:29,846
<i>SWIFTY: I got $500,000.</i>

303
00:16:29,923 --> 00:16:31,322
Is that good?

304
00:16:31,391 --> 00:16:36,021
<i>Mr. President,
it's a half a million dollars
for a news interview.</i>

305
00:16:36,095 --> 00:16:37,357
<i>It's unprecedented.</i>

306
00:16:37,430 --> 00:16:39,625
<i>Yeah? Well, what's the catch?</i>

307
00:16:39,699 --> 00:16:42,863
<i>With Frost? None.
It'll be a big wet kiss.</i>

308
00:16:43,437 --> 00:16:46,065
<i>This guy'll be so grateful
to be getting it at all,</i>

309
00:16:46,140 --> 00:16:47,834
<i>he'll pitch
puffballs all night</i>

310
00:16:47,907 --> 00:16:50,740
<i>and pay a half
a million dollars
for the privilege.</i>

311
00:16:54,113 --> 00:16:56,479
Well, you think
you could get 550?

312
00:16:57,784 --> 00:16:59,115
<i>I got 6.</i>

313
00:17:00,820 --> 00:17:02,685
BIRT: David, how could
you have done that?
What?

314
00:17:02,755 --> 00:17:04,690
<i>$600,000. That's a fortune.</i>

315
00:17:04,758 --> 00:17:05,747
200 on signature?

316
00:17:05,826 --> 00:17:07,293
<i>Don't worry about the money.</i>

317
00:17:07,361 --> 00:17:09,727
<i>My God.
Most Americans think
he belongs in jail.</i>

318
00:17:09,797 --> 00:17:11,491
<i>You're making him
a rich man.</i>

319
00:17:11,564 --> 00:17:13,498
<i>Plus, by outbidding them,
you've already made enemies</i>

320
00:17:13,566 --> 00:17:15,056
<i>of the networks.
They're just jealous.</i>

321
00:17:15,134 --> 00:17:17,659
<i>They're already sounding off
about checkbook journalism.</i>

322
00:17:17,737 --> 00:17:19,170
And if the networks
are against you,

323
00:17:19,238 --> 00:17:20,637
<i>syndication's always
going to be a struggle.</i>

324
00:17:20,707 --> 00:17:22,265
<i>No syndication,
no advance sales.</i>

325
00:17:22,342 --> 00:17:23,867
<i>No advance sales,
no commercials.</i>

326
00:17:23,944 --> 00:17:25,377
<i>No commercials, no revenue.</i>

327
00:17:25,446 --> 00:17:29,110
<i>And here's the bigger
question, why do it?
You don't need it.</i>

328
00:17:29,184 --> 00:17:30,310
<i>Your career's
in great shape.</i>

329
00:17:30,385 --> 00:17:32,546
This will just spread you
across three continents,

330
00:17:32,620 --> 00:17:34,211
<i>jeopardize the other shows.</i>

331
00:17:34,288 --> 00:17:35,687
<i>Isn't it true that
Channel Nine in Australia</i>

332
00:17:35,756 --> 00:17:37,451
want you to do
another season
of your talk show for them?

333
00:17:37,524 --> 00:17:38,582
<i>Yes.
And London, too?</i>

334
00:17:38,659 --> 00:17:40,786
<i>Yes, but that would be
London and Australia.</i>

335
00:17:40,861 --> 00:17:42,624
<i>This would be...
What?</i>

336
00:17:43,230 --> 00:17:44,720
<i>You wouldn't
understand, John.</i>

337
00:17:44,798 --> 00:17:47,631
You were never
part of the show
in New York,

338
00:17:48,268 --> 00:17:50,065
<i>but it's indescribable.</i>

339
00:17:50,137 --> 00:17:55,201
<i>Success in America
is unlike success
anywhere else.</i>

340
00:17:56,643 --> 00:17:58,668
<i>And the emptiness
when it's gone.</i>

341
00:18:00,080 --> 00:18:05,518
<i>And the sickening
thought that it may
never come back.</i>

342
00:18:06,453 --> 00:18:08,819
<i>You know, there's
a restaurant in New York
called Sardi's.</i>

343
00:18:08,889 --> 00:18:10,652
<i>Ordinary mortals
can't get a table.</i>

344
00:18:10,724 --> 00:18:12,419
John, the place
was my canteen!

345
00:18:12,493 --> 00:18:13,585
<i>You know, I'd be happier</i>

346
00:18:13,660 --> 00:18:14,889
if I heard
some kind of vision

347
00:18:14,963 --> 00:18:16,123
<i>that you had
for this interview.</i>

348
00:18:16,197 --> 00:18:17,357
<i>MAN: Excuse me, Mr. Frost.</i>

349
00:18:17,432 --> 00:18:18,557
<i>I'd heard you were
going to be here.</i>

350
00:18:18,632 --> 00:18:20,566
<i>Would you mind?
Of course.</i>

351
00:18:20,634 --> 00:18:22,124
<i>But I don't.
I just hear
a man doing it</i>

352
00:18:22,202 --> 00:18:23,464
because it would
create headlines

353
00:18:23,537 --> 00:18:25,630
<i>or give him a place
at the top table.</i>

354
00:18:25,706 --> 00:18:27,071
<i>And that is what
makes me nervous.</i>

355
00:18:27,141 --> 00:18:29,871
<i>And you do nervous
so beautifully, John.</i>

356
00:18:29,943 --> 00:18:33,243
<i>"Hello, good evening
and welcome."</i>

357
00:18:33,715 --> 00:18:35,239
(FROST LAUGHS)

358
00:18:36,451 --> 00:18:38,386
<i>I don't actually say that.</i>

359
00:18:38,454 --> 00:18:40,012
<i>Hello, Mr. Frost.</i>

360
00:18:46,594 --> 00:18:47,822
Champagne?

361
00:18:47,896 --> 00:18:49,591
<i>CAROLINE: No, thank you.</i>

362
00:18:50,598 --> 00:18:52,657
FLIGHT ATTENDANT:
Another glass, sir?

363
00:19:10,185 --> 00:19:12,346
<i>You don't like champagne?</i>

364
00:19:13,822 --> 00:19:15,380
<i>Not on airplanes.</i>

365
00:19:15,457 --> 00:19:17,755
<i>Yes, it dehydrates
one terribly.</i>

366
00:19:18,593 --> 00:19:21,255
<i>The trick is to have
a glass of water
on the go, too.</i>

367
00:19:21,329 --> 00:19:23,854
<i>Like the Viennese
serve coffee.</i>

368
00:19:23,932 --> 00:19:26,196
<i>Well, I've never
been to Vienna.</i>

369
00:19:26,267 --> 00:19:28,735
<i>Oh. Well, you'd like it.</i>

370
00:19:28,803 --> 00:19:31,829
<i>It's like Paris
without the French.</i>

371
00:19:34,843 --> 00:19:36,401
<i>What's your name?</i>

372
00:19:36,478 --> 00:19:37,672
<i>Caroline.</i>

373
00:19:37,745 --> 00:19:38,769
<i>David.</i>

374
00:19:38,847 --> 00:19:41,544
<i>Yes, I know. David Frost.</i>

375
00:19:42,551 --> 00:19:45,349
<i>"Hello and good evening
and welcome."</i>

376
00:19:50,092 --> 00:19:53,789
<i>You know, I heard
an interview with you
recently on the radio.</i>

377
00:19:53,863 --> 00:19:56,195
<i>You were giving it
from the back
of your Rolls-Royce.</i>

378
00:19:56,265 --> 00:19:57,391
<i>Bentley.</i>

379
00:19:57,466 --> 00:19:58,524
<i>On the phone.</i>

380
00:19:58,601 --> 00:19:59,863
They said that
you were a person

381
00:19:59,935 --> 00:20:02,961
<i>who defined
the age we live in.</i>

382
00:20:03,038 --> 00:20:04,630
<i>Really?
Mmm.</i>

383
00:20:05,174 --> 00:20:06,766
<i>You and Vidal Sassoon.</i>

384
00:20:08,477 --> 00:20:11,445
But what made you
exceptional, they said,

385
00:20:11,513 --> 00:20:15,450
was that you were a person
who had achieved great fame

386
00:20:15,518 --> 00:20:18,885
<i>without possessing
any discernible quality.</i>

387
00:20:18,954 --> 00:20:20,182
<i>How kind.
Mmm-hmm.</i>

388
00:20:20,256 --> 00:20:23,555
<i>And that you fly
around a great deal.</i>

389
00:20:23,626 --> 00:20:25,924
<i>Well, that's true.</i>

390
00:20:26,829 --> 00:20:27,818
Why?

391
00:20:27,897 --> 00:20:29,387
<i>I like to keep busy.</i>

392
00:20:30,032 --> 00:20:31,431
Why?

393
00:20:31,500 --> 00:20:34,060
<i>I find it
more interesting
than keeping still.</i>

394
00:20:35,136 --> 00:20:37,071
<i>You know,
you have very sad eyes.</i>

395
00:20:37,773 --> 00:20:39,570
<i>Do I?
Mmm.</i>

396
00:20:39,642 --> 00:20:41,633
Has anyone told
you that before?

397
00:20:42,178 --> 00:20:43,440
<i>No.</i>

398
00:20:43,512 --> 00:20:45,173
Are you a sad person?

399
00:20:49,051 --> 00:20:51,612
<i>Let's talk about
you a little bit.</i>

400
00:20:51,688 --> 00:20:54,179
<i>Of course, you feel more
comfortable asking questions.</i>

401
00:20:54,257 --> 00:20:56,191
How right you are!

402
00:20:56,526 --> 00:20:58,254
<i>This is your
captain speaking.</i>

403
00:20:58,327 --> 00:20:59,316
<i>You may have
noticed we've begun</i>

404
00:20:59,396 --> 00:21:01,523
<i>our final descent
into Los Angeles.</i>

405
00:21:02,432 --> 00:21:05,492
<i>If you could please
return to your seats
and fasten your seat belts,</i>

406
00:21:05,569 --> 00:21:07,628
<i>we'll be landing
very shortly. Thank you.</i>

407
00:21:07,704 --> 00:21:10,002
CAROLINE: So how about you?
Where are you going?

408
00:21:10,073 --> 00:21:12,439
<i>To meet Richard Nixon.</i>

409
00:21:12,509 --> 00:21:13,737
Really?

410
00:21:15,412 --> 00:21:18,210
You know, they say he has
the most enormous head,

411
00:21:18,682 --> 00:21:20,239
<i>but the sexiest voice.</i>

412
00:21:20,316 --> 00:21:21,681
Where is he now?

413
00:21:21,951 --> 00:21:25,479
In some dark underground cave
licking his wounds?

414
00:21:26,356 --> 00:21:29,120
<i>Actually, no.
In his rather smart
beachside villa</i>

415
00:21:29,192 --> 00:21:30,250
<i>in California.</i>

416
00:21:30,327 --> 00:21:33,057
Really? Richard Nixon
in a beachside villa?

417
00:21:33,129 --> 00:21:34,721
<i>How incongruous.</i>

418
00:21:34,798 --> 00:21:36,766
<i>You can come if you'd like.</i>

419
00:21:37,267 --> 00:21:38,928
To meet Nixon?

420
00:21:39,669 --> 00:21:41,364
Why not?

421
00:21:42,738 --> 00:21:44,035
Are you sure?

422
00:21:47,077 --> 00:21:48,772
<i>You know, I would love that.</i>

423
00:21:48,845 --> 00:21:51,006
<i>PILOT: Cabin crew,
please prepare for arrival.</i>

424
00:21:51,081 --> 00:21:53,948
<i>Well, I'll get
my office to call you
first thing in the morning</i>

425
00:21:54,017 --> 00:21:56,577
<i>and send a car with a phone.</i>

426
00:21:56,653 --> 00:21:57,642
<i>Oh.</i>

427
00:22:00,091 --> 00:22:03,151
<i>He did, too. Money no object.</i>

428
00:22:03,227 --> 00:22:07,219
<i>Everything glittered
and was golden.</i>

429
00:22:07,297 --> 00:22:08,764
<i>Well, on the outside.</i>

430
00:22:08,832 --> 00:22:11,666
<i>Of course, what I didn't know
was that in the meantime,</i>

431
00:22:11,736 --> 00:22:13,897
<i>he'd gone to all
the major networks</i>

432
