carry that burden with me</i>

1923
01:47:05,055 --> 01:47:07,080
<i>for the rest of my life.</i>

1924
01:47:18,803 --> 01:47:21,203
<i>My political life is over.</i>

1925
01:47:49,098 --> 01:47:53,331
You know, the first
and greatest sin
or deception of television

1926
01:47:53,404 --> 01:47:56,862
is that it simplifies,
it diminishes,

1927
01:47:57,174 --> 01:48:01,634
<i>great, complex ideas,
tranches of time.</i>

1928
01:48:02,446 --> 01:48:06,645
<i>Whole careers become reduced
to a single snapshot.</i>

1929
01:48:07,619 --> 01:48:09,813
<i>At first, I couldn't
understand why</i>

1930
01:48:09,887 --> 01:48:12,253
Bob Zelnick was
quite as euphoric

1931
01:48:12,323 --> 01:48:14,519
<i>as he was after
the interviews,</i>

1932
01:48:17,362 --> 01:48:21,128
<i>or why John Birt felt
moved to strip naked</i>

1933
01:48:21,199 --> 01:48:24,066
<i>and rush into
the ocean to celebrate.</i>

1934
01:48:24,135 --> 01:48:28,834
But that was before
I really understood

1935
01:48:28,907 --> 01:48:31,704
<i>the reductive power
of the close-up.</i>

1936
01:48:31,775 --> 01:48:35,643
Because David had
succeeded on that final day

1937
01:48:35,713 --> 01:48:37,510
in getting,
for a fleeting moment,

1938
01:48:37,581 --> 01:48:39,106
what no investigative
journalist,

1939
01:48:39,184 --> 01:48:42,881
no state prosecutor,
no judiciary committee

1940
01:48:42,954 --> 01:48:46,117
<i>or political enemy
had managed to get.</i>

1941
01:48:46,358 --> 01:48:48,724
<i>Richard Nixon's face,</i>

1942
01:48:48,793 --> 01:48:54,458
<i>swollen and ravaged
by loneliness,
self-loathing and defeat.</i>

1943
01:48:55,900 --> 01:48:59,597
<i>The rest of the project
and its failings would
not only be forgotten,</i>

1944
01:48:59,670 --> 01:49:01,935
<i>they would totally
cease to exist.</i>

1945
01:49:03,742 --> 01:49:05,209
(CAMERAS CLICKING)

1946
01:49:05,577 --> 01:49:07,272
(REPORTERS CLAMORING)

1947
01:49:09,648 --> 01:49:12,209
<i>REPORTER: Who came out
on top, Mr. President?</i>

1948
01:49:31,971 --> 01:49:34,337
Is this what you
call a dachshund?

1949
01:49:34,407 --> 01:49:35,533
<i>Mmm-hmm.</i>

1950
01:49:44,015 --> 01:49:45,346
<i>Very sweet.</i>

1951
01:49:56,462 --> 01:49:57,861
(ENGINE STARTING)

1952
01:50:16,349 --> 01:50:19,375
<i>The Nixon/Frost interviews
were wildly successful.</i>

1953
01:50:19,452 --> 01:50:22,013
I think they attracted
the largest audience
for a news program

1954
01:50:22,089 --> 01:50:23,784
<i>in the history of
American television.</i>

1955
01:50:23,857 --> 01:50:26,984
<i>David was on
the cover of Time magazine
and Newsweek magazine.</i>

1956
01:50:27,059 --> 01:50:28,321
<i>And even the political
press corps,</i>

1957
01:50:28,394 --> 01:50:29,588
<i>the hard-bitten
political press corps,</i>

1958
01:50:29,662 --> 01:50:32,631
<i>called David up with
messages of contrition
and congratulation.</i>

1959
01:50:32,698 --> 01:50:34,893
<i>David, I want to
say congratulations.</i>

1960
01:50:35,001 --> 01:50:36,833
The interviews?

1961
01:50:36,903 --> 01:50:40,339
<i>No, I didn't watch them.
I couldn't.</i>

1962
01:50:41,141 --> 01:50:42,631
<i>(DISCO MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

1963
01:50:42,709 --> 01:50:43,698
<i>Hey.</i>

1964
01:50:45,579 --> 01:50:46,739
<i>Hello.</i>

1965
01:50:54,487 --> 01:50:57,718
<i>I believe David saw
the former President
just one more time.</i>

1966
01:50:57,790 --> 01:50:59,622
Before he left California
for London again,

1967
01:50:59,693 --> 01:51:02,287
<i>he drove down
to San Clemente
to say goodbye.</i>

1968
01:51:14,473 --> 01:51:17,704
<i>Hey, Mr. Frost.
It's nice to see you.</i>

1969
01:51:18,644 --> 01:51:20,202
<i>Miss Cushing.
Hello.</i>

1970
01:51:21,380 --> 01:51:23,508
<i>Please excuse
my golf outfit.</i>

1971
01:51:23,583 --> 01:51:26,552
<i>It's the official
uniform of the retired.</i>

1972
01:51:27,988 --> 01:51:29,479
Are you on your way home?

1973
01:51:29,557 --> 01:51:30,751
<i>Yes.</i>

1974
01:51:30,825 --> 01:51:35,921
Into a bright new dawn
of fresh enterprises
and challenges, eh?

1975
01:51:35,996 --> 01:51:37,224
<i>Well, let's hope so.</i>

1976
01:51:37,297 --> 01:51:38,491
<i>Good for you.</i>

1977
01:51:38,565 --> 01:51:41,500
<i>I didn't catch
the interviews
as they went out,</i>

1978
01:51:41,568 --> 01:51:45,197
<i>but they tell me
that they were
a great success.</i>

1979
01:51:45,272 --> 01:51:49,004
I gather the journalists
that were so positive

1980
01:51:49,077 --> 01:51:52,069
<i>about you weren't
so kind to me.</i>

1981
01:51:52,146 --> 01:51:55,138
<i>Yes, I was sorry to see that.</i>

1982
01:51:55,816 --> 01:51:58,080
<i>There's no
condolences necessary.</i>

1983
01:51:58,151 --> 01:52:00,711
<i>I've grown to
expect nothing else
from those sons of whores.</i>

1984
01:52:00,787 --> 01:52:02,482
<i>Yeah.</i>

1985
01:52:02,589 --> 01:52:05,752
<i>Jeez, please forgive me,
Miss Cushing.</i>

1986
01:52:06,159 --> 01:52:09,322
<i>You know,
I would've said
"sons of bitches,"</i>

1987
01:52:09,396 --> 01:52:12,025
but Manolo here
is a lover of dogs,

1988
01:52:12,100 --> 01:52:14,398
<i>and he hates me
to defame animals.</i>

1989
01:52:14,869 --> 01:52:16,496
Can I get something
for somebody?

1990
01:52:16,571 --> 01:52:19,004
<i>Yes. Would you like
some tea or champagne?</i>

1991
01:52:19,072 --> 01:52:22,303
<i>Hey, you know,
we got that caviar
the Shah of Iran sent me.</i>

1992
01:52:22,375 --> 01:52:23,433
<i>No, thank you.
You sure?</i>

1993
01:52:23,510 --> 01:52:24,807
<i>Come on. It'll be
no trouble at all.</i>

1994
01:52:24,878 --> 01:52:26,106
<i>No, really, we must be...</i>

1995
01:52:26,179 --> 01:52:29,876
<i>Okay, fine, fine.
Thanks for coming by.</i>

1996
01:52:32,953 --> 01:52:35,184
<i>You were a worthy opponent.</i>

1997
01:52:37,191 --> 01:52:38,352
<i>Goodbye, Mr. President.</i>

1998
01:52:38,427 --> 01:52:39,724
<i>Bye-bye.</i>

1999
01:52:39,795 --> 01:52:41,193
<i>Goodbye, Mr. President.</i>

2000
01:52:41,262 --> 01:52:42,286
<i>Goodbye.</i>

2001
01:52:44,031 --> 01:52:46,659
<i>Oh, God!
I almost forgot. I...</i>

2002
01:52:47,668 --> 01:52:53,573
<i>I brought you a present,
those shoes you admired.</i>

2003
01:52:53,875 --> 01:52:55,638
<i>I brought you a pair.</i>

2004
01:52:56,811 --> 01:52:59,804
<i>Well, jeez. Thank you.</i>

2005
01:53:04,519 --> 01:53:09,684
<i>I'm touched. Safe trip, now.</i>

2006
01:53:14,061 --> 01:53:19,795
Oh! Say, David, you think
I could speak to you,
privately, just for a minute?

2007
01:53:31,145 --> 01:53:33,739
Do you know those
parties of yours?

2008
01:53:33,815 --> 01:53:36,283
The ones that I read about
in all the papers?

2009
01:53:36,350 --> 01:53:39,080
Do you actually enjoy those?

2010
01:53:39,987 --> 01:53:41,352
<i>Of course.</i>

2011
01:53:42,890 --> 01:53:46,793
<i>You got no idea how
fortunate that makes you.</i>

2012
01:53:47,964 --> 01:53:52,263
<i>You know?
Liking people,
and being liked.</i>

2013
01:53:52,334 --> 01:53:56,998
<i>Having that facility,
that lightness, that charm.</i>

2014
01:53:58,473 --> 01:54:00,907
<i>I don't have it.
I never did.</i>

2015
01:54:01,710 --> 01:54:04,543
It kind of makes you wonder
why I chose a life

2016
01:54:04,613 --> 01:54:07,707
<i>that hinged on being liked.</i>

2017
01:54:08,017 --> 01:54:11,417
<i>I'm better suited
to a life of thought,</i>

2018
01:54:11,486 --> 01:54:13,716
<i>debate,
intellectual discipline.</i>

2019
01:54:14,756 --> 01:54:15,984
<i>Maybe we got it wrong.</i>

2020
01:54:16,058 --> 01:54:17,923
Maybe you should have
been a politician

2021
01:54:17,993 --> 01:54:20,325
<i>and I the rigorous
interviewer.</i>

2022
01:54:20,963 --> 01:54:22,225
<i>Maybe.</i>

2023
01:54:23,665 --> 01:54:24,791
<i>David.</i>

2024
01:54:27,135 --> 01:54:30,593
Did I really
call you that night?

2025
01:54:32,942 --> 01:54:34,135
<i>Yes.</i>

2026
01:54:35,043 --> 01:54:38,877
Did we discuss
anything important?

2027
01:54:43,151 --> 01:54:44,618
<i>Cheeseburgers.</i>

2028
01:54:47,022 --> 01:54:48,580
Cheeseburgers?

2029
01:54:54,296 --> 01:54:55,787
<i>Goodbye, sir.</i>

2030
01:55:05,975 --> 01:55:08,136
<i>RESTON: Well, New York,
London and Sydney</i>

2031
01:55:08,211 --> 01:55:10,645
<i>welcomed David
back with open arms,</i>

2032
01:55:10,713 --> 01:55:12,442
<i>as did his friends
and investors,</i>

2033
01:55:12,515 --> 01:55:14,983
<i>who've made a fortune
from these interviews.</i>

2034
01:55:15,051 --> 01:55:16,643
<i>He got back all of his shows.</i>

2035
01:55:16,719 --> 01:55:18,984
<i>He even got back
his table at Sardi's.</i>

2036
01:55:19,756 --> 01:55:21,121
<i>As for Richard Nixon,</i>

2037
01:55:21,190 --> 01:55:22,418
<i>well, he certainly
never achieved</i>

2038
01:55:22,492 --> 01:55:25,188
<i>the rehabilitation
he so desperately craved.</i>

2039
01:55:25,261 --> 01:55:27,422
His most lasting legacy

2040
01:55:27,497 --> 01:55:30,295
is that today
any political wrongdoing

2041
01:55:30,400 --> 01:55:33,198
<i>is immediately given
the suffix "gate."</i>

